<h2 style="font-family:verdana; color:#333">Number Bond</h2>

<div style="line-height:2">
<p style="font-family:verdana; color:#333">The Number Bond diagram consists of a "Whole" and two "Parts". It shows us how a number can be split into two parts.</p>

<p style="font-family:verdana; color:#333">Drag the counters into the 3 boxes of the number bond diagram and the numbers will reflect on the 3 circles number bond diagram. Click the button<img src="https://alfaandfriends.com/maths-digitaltools/00-icons/ui_visibility.png" width="40" height="40" style="vertical-align:middle">to make the numbers in the circles appear and disappear.</p>

<p style="font-family:verdana; color:#333">Here are a few ways to use the number bond diagram:
<ul style="font-family:verdana; color:#333">
<li>Provide the children with the "Whole" and get them to explore the different combination of number to get the sum (number in the whole circle). 
<li>Provide the children the "Whole" and a "Part". Then, get them to find the unknown "Part".
<li>Provide the children with the two "Parts" and get them to find the "Whole".
</ul>
</p>

<p style="font-family:verdana; color:#333">Use the<img src="https://alfaandfriends.com/maths-digitaltools/00-icons/ui_eraser.png" width="40" height="40" style="vertical-align:middle">or<img src="https://alfaandfriends.com/maths-digitaltools/00-icons/ui_clear.png" width="40" height="40" style="vertical-align:middle">button to remove all the scribbles with the pencil tool. To start counting a new set of numbers, click the<img src="https://alfaandfriends.com/maths-digitaltools/00-icons/ui_reset.png" width="40" height="40" style="vertical-align:middle">button.</p>
</div>